Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for compiling a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <!-- Project Information -->
    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>

    <!-- Project Name and Description -->
    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <!-- Project Properties -->
    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <!-- Project Dependencies -->
    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <!-- Project Build Settings -->
    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>

The LCD screen is connected to the Arduino board via a LiquidCrystal I2C library, which can be installed through the Arduino IDE [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

The potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the LCD panel. One pin of the potentiometer is connected to the VCC pin on the Arduino board, while the other pin is connected to pin 3 on the LCD screen [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

The code can be written to read the temperature from the temperature sensor and display it on the LCD screen. They work closely with the product manager to understand the product requirements and goals. The product designer creates wireframes, sketches, and prototypes to visualize the product and test its usability. They also work with the engineering team to ensure that the design is feasible and meets the technical requirements. The product designer iterates on the design based on feedback from stakeholders and testing results.
